John Edward: The Language Skills That the World's Citizens Need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with yet another package of outstanding exam results, and added weight to this by individual and joint successes in sport, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement this school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language that he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it goes to his heart.”
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of this year's final exams show that the highest scores in languages were achieved by students from independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received an excellent score for Mandarin, while 72% of students learning German, 69% of students learning French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest score possible.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of a language-skilled workforce.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs demand knowledge of languages, these skills are key in a globalised world.
Regardless of the choice of career, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such a long-term skill.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, and this gives them an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4000 adults in 2013, 75% of respondents in the UK do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language that speaks a bilingual percentage of respondents, namely 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of countries with a developing economy, they will have more opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland, each school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will choose the languages considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a diverse selection, as well as teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which learners will prepare and equip themselves with the skills necessary for success, no matter what the future holds for us.
We cannot ignore the fact that in today's global business, knowledge of the language is very important for the future of each country, so it must also be reflected in education.
Therefore, knowledge of modern languages should really be seen as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer a choice of language, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It has to be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
