Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim made a promise to work on “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea wants to formally end the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States has insisted that Pyongyang give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also ignored calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on denuclearization and increases the pressure through sanctions to forcefully achieve its goal, and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to the war,'" he said.
