Harvard students take a course on how to get a good rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to sleep well in an attempt to combat an increasingly widespread culture of learning with caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academic has found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea for the course after giving a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, “Why did I find out about this only now, in my last year of college?”
She said no one told her how important the dream was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and sports success and generally improve health.
Professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of the University’s Health Service Paul Barreira says the University has decided to introduce the course after students noticed a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a student dormitory where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how lack of sleep affects success and how important a sleep routine is.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
After that, a campus map with interactive icons is displayed that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in all-day learning before the exam still exists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it into a state of hunger and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his lectures in Harvard's first year.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, he plans to ask all graduate students to complete a similar course of study before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on the alarm during sleep as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
