Health workers say more than 820,000 people have been infected in the country.
About 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new infections are transmitted by sex, which is a change from the past.
In the past, HIV was rapidly transmitted throughout some parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
At a conference in Yunnan province, Chinese health authorities said that a person infected with HIV in this way is almost absent.
However, every year the number of people living with HIV and AIDS increases by 100,000 people.
The transmission of the HIV virus through sex is a constant problem among the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be high.
Studies estimate that due to conservative values in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of disease transmission in such relationships occur due to inadequate protection during sex.
As part of efforts to address this problem, the Chinese government promised free access to HIV drugs in 2003.
